Â @sunainavamshi5961Â   Thanks to Google:
I am from Sydney :


No, internship and house surgery are not the same. Internship, also known as housemanship or PGY1 training, is the first year of postgraduate training for medical graduates in Australia, while house surgery is not a recognized term in medical training. 

Internship: First year of clinical training after medical school, often focused on broad exposure to different specialties.
Housemanship: A subsequent period of training, often involving more responsibility and independence in patient care.
The usage of these terms can vary by country, so it's important to consider the context in which they are used.

General information.. When you see National Medical Commission & Dental council of India regulations, if you have to practice facial cosmetic procedures or hair transplant procedures in India you have to be a Certified Plastic surgeon or a certified Dermatologist or a certified Maxillofacial surgeon.. Rest all other doctors were not eligible to practice these procedures in India..  So if any clinic have these doctors you can consult them..

Spilling some facts for the unaware-
1) Harshitha did engineering and later took a course in Cosmetology(probably 6months-1yr course). So now she became a cosmetologist(not a dermatologist). Cosmetology is a course which can be taken by anybody (even if you are just 10th pass, or you did Hotel management or engineering or bpharma or you are entirely from a different profession also, you can take up cosmetology course.)
2) As a cosmetologist if you want to start a clinic NOT just for eyebrow colouring or lip colouring but want to treat acne, prescribe medicines, do hair transplantations or similar medical procedures, that should at all costs be under the supervision of a dermatologist (someone who completed MBBS and did PG in Dermatology).
3) Now what actually went wrong with HK clinic is that Harshita claimed herself to be a doctor in her instagram reels by wearing apron and scrubs with her name mentioned on her scrubs as Dr.Harshita. She received a doctorate degree(not a doctor degree!!) from some foreign university and started claiming herself to be a doctor by keeping the prefix Dr before her name. In her case- (Hon) Dr. Harshita should be mentioned instead of Dr.Harshita as thereâ€™s head to toe difference between both of them.
4) For all their branches, they have managed to only keep 1 actual dermatologist (thereâ€™s solid proof) instead of atleast 1/branch. So doing dermat procedures without doctor supervision is terribly wrong and illegal.
5) Now that ppl are getting aware of all this stuff, she posted a reel saying â€œIm not a dermat and I dont do any procedures, I just stand thereâ€.
6) Social media these days is influencing ppl so much so that they started believing anything and everything they see. Dont be fools, have basic awareness dear ppl.
The same is the issue with Layers clinic- Dr.Kaumudi is a dentist who later took up cometology course and became a cosmetologist. They too hired only a single dermatologist for all their 7 branches instead of atleast 1/branch, meaning they are doing procedures without any supervision and some other cosmetologists who are prescribing medications which is illegal.
taking into consideration the hefty amounts they charge for each procedure, they shouldnâ€™t play with peopleâ€™s lives.
Hope this helped anyone whoâ€™s unaware of these things.

Ms. Mandava must also acknowledge a fundamental aspect of medical practice: asking about a patient's history â€” including alcohol use, smoking habits, or sexual activity â€” is standard and essential across all disciplines. These are not intrusive or inappropriate questions; they are clinical necessities that guide diagnosis and determine safe, effective treatment plans.

In todays context, where substance use and risky behaviors are prevalent among the younger population, it becomes all the more critical for doctors to inquire about such factors with sensitivity and professionalism. If someone feels offended by such questions, it reflects a lack of understanding of how medicine functions â€” not a fault on the part of the practitioner.

As medical professionals, we are trained to approach these topics with discretion and care. Patients, in turn, must understand that such discussions are integral to their care and safety.

Despite being a well-established and authorized salon, the lack of truly professional staff has become increasingly apparent. Unfortunately, this was my experience at a particular salon (which I prefer not to name). I invested a significant amount in a treatment that did not meet expectations, and it was a disappointing experienceâ€”enough for me to decide that I will no longer pursue salon treatments.

The core issue seems to be staffing. When skilled professionals are not offered competitive compensation, itâ€™s understandable that they seek opportunities elsewhere. As a result, salons often resort to hiring untrained or minimally trained individuals and provide only a basic salary. Given the employment landscape in India, there is no shortage of people willing to work for such wages, but this approach severely compromises the quality of service.

The Tehri Dam in Uttarakhand is the highest dam in India, standing at a height of 260.5 meters. It's also among the top ten highest dams in the world and is situated on the Bhagirathi River.

Foreigners appreciation tweets  telustai. Avi pattinchukokunda elli aa koratala gadni pattukunte em labham. Meeku kgf laga boggu colour face meeda kottevade correct. Kgf part 1 nice film, Kgf 2 headache music. 5 minutes ko high movement, ivvi tappa story emaina nadichinda. Vaadu VIRAT ni champinappude veedo criminal tappa, em kadu ani ardham ayyindi. Adheera 4 scenes. Endukostado vadike teleedu. Emotion leni Elevations enduku. If you say minute to minute high movements than AKHANDA >>>>>>>> KGF2. NTR fans anta evarikaina choopinchukondi, maa hero character over expect chesam, maa limit sky lo undi, kanee anta reach avvaledu kabatti tattukolekapotunnam ani.
